# PID Simulation — Agent SOP

Standard operating procedure for AI agents working on Mantik’s browser-based PID tuning trainer (`/pid-simulation`). Applies to **any mechanism** (elevator, arm, shooter, turret, etc.).

Read [`CLAUDE.md`](../../CLAUDE.md) for project handoff. This document captures **mistakes already made** and how to avoid repeating them.

---

## 1. What this product is (and is not)

| Is | Is not |
|----|--------|
| Training sim: edit boilerplate, tune gains, watch mechanism + graph | Real WPILib JVM, Gradle, YAMS runtime |
| Parser extracts constants from Java templates | Arbitrary Java compile/execute |
| Workflow mirror of Elastic / AdvantageScope / vendor tuners | Byte-identical copy of YAMS or desktop sim |

Link students to [mantik-pid-practice](https://github.com/itkan-robotics/mantik-pid-practice) for full local WPILib sim.

**Before implementing physics for a mechanism:** find the reference plant in mantik-pid-practice (or FRC lesson) and note **motor type**, **mass/inertia**, **gearing**, and **expected gain ranges** from the lesson video. Calibrate to those ranges — not to generic guesses.

---

## 2. Physics — do not skip calibration

### 2.1 Feedforward shape ≠ correct plant

**Mistake:** Used correct WPILib feedforward equation (`kG + kS·sgn(v) + kV·v + kA·a`) but ad-hoc plant constants. kG tuning was meaningless (needed ~7 V; lesson expects ~0.6 V).

**Rule:** Feedforward and plant must be calibrated **together**. A correct formula with a wrong plant still fails.

### 2.2 Use WPILib motor + plant models

**Mistake:** Invented `MOTOR_KT`, linear torque, fixed friction. Did not match `LinearSystemId` or lesson repo.

**Rule for any mechanism:**

1. Port `DCMotor` constants from WPILib (`edu.wpi.first.math.system.plant.DCMotor`) — use the **same motor** as the reference repo (e.g. mantik-pid-practice elevator uses `getNEO(1)`, not Neo550).
2. Build plant matrices from WPILib `LinearSystemId` for that mechanism type:
   - **Linear (elevator):** `createElevatorSystem` — state `[position, velocity]`, gravity as `-g` on acceleration.
   - **Rotational (arm, turret):** `createSingleJointedArmSystem` — gravity term scales with `cos(angle)`.
   - **Velocity (flywheel, shooter):** no position PID / no kG; `kV` dominates; different state and tuning workflow.
3. Integrate with **WPILib RKDP** (`NumericalIntegration.rkdp`) on the full `[position, velocity]` state — see [`numericalIntegration.ts`](../../src/lib/pid-sim/physics/numericalIntegration.ts) and [`linearSystemSim.ts`](../../src/lib/pid-sim/physics/linearSystemSim.ts). Gravity is added as `[0, -9.8]` on `xdot`, matching `ElevatorSim.updateX`. Do **not** use naive Euler on the plant.

**WPILib reference (authoritative):**

- [wpilibj.simulation package](https://github.wpilib.org/allwpilib/docs/release/java/edu/wpi/first/wpilibj/simulation/package-summary.html)
- [LinearSystemSim](https://github.wpilib.org/allwpilib/docs/release/java/edu/wpi/first/wpilibj/simulation/LinearSystemSim.html)
- [ElevatorSim](https://github.wpilib.org/allwpilib/docs/release/java/edu/wpi/first/wpilibj/simulation/ElevatorSim.html)
- [NumericalIntegration.rkdp](https://github.wpilib.org/allwpilib/docs/release/java/edu/wpi/first/math/system/NumericalIntegration.html)
- [Tuning a vertical elevator (WPILib docs)](https://docs.wpilib.org/en/stable/docs/software/advanced-controls/introduction/tuning-elevator.html)
- Source: [LinearSystemSim.java](https://github.com/wpilibsuite/allwpilib/blob/main/wpilibj/src/main/java/edu/wpi/first/wpilibj/simulation/LinearSystemSim.java), [ElevatorSim.java](https://github.com/wpilibsuite/allwpilib/blob/main/wpilibj/src/main/java/edu/wpi/first/wpilibj/simulation/ElevatorSim.java)

**Browser architecture (hybrid):**

- **Plant:** `ElevatorSimPlant` — faithful WPILib plant (RKDP, gravity, limit snap, voltage clamp). No artificial damping, no plant-side motion caps.
- **Wrapper:** `elevatorSim.ts` — PID + feedforward + trapezoid profile. kP is WPILib-native (V/m); `pidOutputScale = 1`. `OPTIMAL_KP` derived from plant matrices via `computeOptimalKpFromPlant()`.

Do **not** return to forward Euler or ad-hoc discrete velocity formulas on the plant unless you re-validate against the WPILib reference.

### 2.3 kG / gravity feedforward

| Mechanism | kG behavior (WPILib) |
|-----------|----------------------|
| Elevator | Constant voltage `kG` |
| Arm / turret | `kG · cos(position)` |
| Flywheel | No kG (velocity plant) |

**Rule:** `computeHoldVoltage()` (or mechanism equivalent) must match steady-state plant math. Assert in unit tests that `kG = holdVoltage` holds position and that `kG` slightly above causes creep in the direction the lesson describes.

### 2.4 kP — WPILib-native units (V/m)

**Mistake:** Scaling kP with `pidOutputScale` to match SparkMax lesson values (~42.5) artificially capped oscillation amplitude — 2× optimal looked like 1×.

**Rule:**

1. Browser sim uses **WPILib-native kP** (V/m): `voltage += kP × error` with no wrapper scale.
2. Derive **`OPTIMAL_KP`** from plant matrices: `computeOptimalKpFromPlant()` targets ζ ≈ 0.75 on the linearized plant.
3. Higher kP → lower ζ → **naturally** larger overshoot and more setpoint crossings in TraceView. Do not add `loopKpFactor` or amplitude calibration hacks.
4. FRC lesson MDX may still cite SparkMax tuner values (~42.5); browser sim and mantik-pid-practice use different kP ranges — document that in hints, not by rescaling physics.

### 2.5 What not to put in the plant

**Mistake:** Fixed `FRICTION_N` in plant while also exposing `kS` in feedforward.

**Rule:** Friction belongs in feedforward (`kS`), not as a hidden plant constant. Hidden plant friction breaks kG/kS pedagogy.

### 2.6 Unit tests required for every new mechanism

Add `*.test.ts` under `src/lib/pid-sim/physics/`:

- Hold voltage / hold kG in lesson range for reference plant
- kG = 0 → mechanism drifts/falls (or spins, for velocity plants)
- kG too high → creeps wrong direction
- kP at `OPTIMAL_KP` → settles faster than low kP, less oscillation than high kP
- kP above oscillation threshold → more velocity zero-crossings or overshoot than optimal

Run: `npm run test:physics`

